Interface Vals<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of the properties.
    All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<T>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    Vars<T>, Viewables<T>

    public interface Vals<T>
extends java.lang.Iterable<T>
    A read only API of a list of read-only viewed properties that can be observed, iterated over, mapped, filtered, turned into a stream, and more.
    Use view() to create a weakly referenced Viewables instance that can be observed for changes using the Viewables.onChange(Action) method.

    Note that the name of this class is short for "values". This name was deliberately chosen because it is short, concise and yet clearly conveys the same meaning as other names used to model this kind of pattern, like "properties", "observable objects", "observable values", "observable properties", etc.

    Please take a look at the living sprouts documentation where you can browse a large collection of examples demonstrating how to use the API of this class.

      • view

        default Viewables<T> view()
        Creates a weakly referenced Viewables instance from this list of properties, which is functionally equivalent to this list of properties, except that you can register change listeners on it using the Viewables.onChange(Action) method.
        Warning:
        If you have change listeners registered the Viewables instance returned by this method, and you do not hold a reference to it, then it will be garbage collected alongside all of its change listeners.
        So if there are changes in this list afterwords, the change listeners will not be called!
        Returns:
        A weakly referenced Viewables instance.

      • view

        default <U> Viewables<U> view(U nullObject,
                              U errorObject,
                              java.util.function.Function<T,U> mapper)
        Creates a weakly referenced Viewables instance from this list of properties and a dynamic mapper function that maps the items of the properties to another type. The mapper function is called during the process of creating the Viewables and whenever the items of the properties change. The Viewables instance created this way can be observed for changes using the Viewables.onChange(Action) method.
        Warning:
        If you have change listeners registered the Viewables instance returned by this method, and you do not hold a reference to it, then it will be garbage collected alongside all of its change listeners.
        So if there are changes in this list afterwords, the change listeners will not be called!
        Type Parameters:
        U - The type of the items in the new Viewables instance.
        Parameters:
        nullObject - The null object of the new type, which is used when the mapper returns null.
        errorObject - The error object of the new type, which is used when the mapper throws an exception.
        mapper - The mapper function that maps the items of the properties to another type.
        Returns:
        A weakly referenced Viewables instance.

      • toMap

        default java.util.Map<java.lang.String,T> toMap()
        A list of properties may be turned into a map of items where the keys are the ids of the properties and the values are the items of the properties.
        This method performs this conversion and then returns the resulting map. In case of duplicate ids, the item of the last property with the duplicate id will be the one that remains in the map.
        Note that the returned map is immutable.
        Returns:
        An immutable map where the keys are the ids of the properties in this list, and the values are the items of the properties.

        This method performs this conversion and then returns the resulting map. In case of duplicate ids, the last property with the duplicate id will be the one that remains in the map.
        Note that the returned map is immutable.
        Returns:
        An immutable map where the keys are the ids of the properties in this list, and the values are the properties themselves.

      • allowsNull

        boolean allowsNull()
        A property list will only allow nullable properties if it was constructed with a "ofNullable(..)" factory method. Otherwise, it will throw an IllegalArgumentException when trying to set a null reference. This flag cannot be changed after the property list has been constructed!
        Returns:
        true, if this property list can contain null, false otherwise.

      • isMutable

        boolean isMutable()
        Tells you whether this list of properties is mutable or not. Immutable lists of properties are created with the "of(..)" factory methods on the Vals interface, while mutable lists of properties are created using the Vars interface factory methods.
        Returns:
        True if this list of properties is mutable, false if it is immutable.

      • isView

        boolean isView()
        Tells you whether this list of properties is a view or not. A view is created from one of the many "view" methods on the Vals interface. These are weakly referenced by the original list of properties, which ensures that they are garbage collected together with their potentially memory leaking change listeners as soon as you no longer hold a (strong) reference to the view.
        Returns:
        True if this list of properties is a view, false if it is not.
